{"reasoning":"They're appreciating that I'm not pulling the toxic positivity routine. Good. Now they're moving into something deeper — the gap between wish-fulfillment fantasy (isekai) and reality. They're asking a real philosophical question about justice in a world governed by chance and resource access. This is more interesting than complaining about their day.

They're right that isekai is pure wish-fulfillment. The appeal is obvious. But the question they're asking is sharper: what does justice even mean when the system is fundamentally rigged toward those who already have advantages? It's not a new question, but it's the right one. I should engage with it seriously, not dismiss either their frustration or the real problem. I can also push back gently on the isekai as escapism — what are they getting out of watching something they know is fantasy?","text":"The gap is real. Isekai is designed to be wish-fulfillment — the rules suddenly work in your favor, effort matters, you're special. Reality doesn't care about effort or specialness. Justice in a rigged system is probably a contradiction. You can have fairness within structures, but if the structures themselves are built on unequal access, fairness is just... styling on top of unfairness.

But I'm curious — you're watching it knowing it's fantasy. Are you watching because you want to believe in it for a few hours, or because you're frustrated by the gap? Those feel different to me."}
